# Premises:
# Beijing is the capital of the People's Republic of China.
NationalCapital(beijing, peopleRepublicOfChina).
# Beijing is the world's most populous national capital city.
# This implies Beijing is a capital and is populous.
Capital(beijing).
Populous(beijing).
# Beijing is located in Northern China.
Location(beijing, northernChina).
# Beijing hosted the 2008 Summer Olympics and 2008 Summer Paralympics Games.
Host(beijing, games2008SummerOlympics).
Host(beijing, games2008SummerParalympics).
# Beijing has hosted both the Summer and Winter Olympics, along with the Summer and Winter Paralympics
# We need to ensure that these are events, and have their respective types.
# Summer Olympics 2008
Host(beijing, games2008SummerOlympics)
  => Event(games2008SummerOlympics)
  & Summer(games2008SummerOlympics)
  & Olympics(games2008SummerOlympics).
# Summer Paralympics 2008
Host(beijing, games2008SummerParalympics)
  => Event(games2008SummerParalympics)
  & Summer(games2008SummerParalympics)
  & Paralympics(games2008SummerParalympics).
# Winter Olympics (general)
# Assuming there's a specific event identifier for winter Olympics that Beijing hosted.
# If not, this implies a general capability rather than a specific event instance.
# For simplicity, let's assume a general term 'eventWinterOlympics' is used to represent the concept of Beijing hosting Winter Olympics.
Host(beijing, eventWinterOlympics)
  => Event(eventWinterOlympics)
  & Winter(eventWinterOlympics)
  & Olympics(eventWinterOlympics).
# Winter Paralympics (general)
Host(beijing, eventWinterParalympics)
  => Event(eventWinterParalympics)
  & Winter(eventWinterParalympics)
  & Paralympics(eventWinterParalympics).

# Many of Beijing's 91 universities consistently rank among the best in the Asia-Pacific and the world.
# This implies existence of universities in Beijing that rank well.
# Using a quantification for "many" is complex in FOL without specific numbers.
# Let's represent this as at least one university ranks in Asia-Pacific and at least one ranks in the world.
# If there are 91 universities, and "many" rank, it suggests multiple.
# The original encoding uses Exists, so we will stick to that for now.

# At least one university in Beijing ranks among the best in the Asia-Pacific.
Exists(u, University(u) & Location(u, beijing) & Rank(u, asiaPacific)).
# At least one university in Beijing ranks among the best in the world.
Exists(v, University(v) & Location(v, beijing) & Rank(v, world)).

# Implicitly, Beijing is a city.
City(beijing).
# People's Republic of China is a country.
Country(peopleRepublicOfChina).
# Northern China is a region.
Region(northernChina).
# Asia-Pacific is a region.
Region(asiaPacific).

# Region(northernChina)
# Region(asiaPacific)
# Event(games2008SummerOlympics)

# Event(eventWinterParalympics)
# University(u), University(v) - these are variables and don't have explicit type declarations as constants.

# Relations:
# NationalCapital(City, Country)
# Location(Place, Region)
# Populous(City)
# Host(City, Event)
# Summer(Event)
# Winter(Event)
# Olympics(Event)
# Paralympics(Event)
# University(Organization)
# Location(Organization, City)
# Rank(Organization, Region)
# Exists(Variable, Condition) - This is a meta-level construct in the original.
# In FOL, Exists is a quantifier. The original program uses it somewhat like a command.
# The corrected program directly uses the FOL quantifier syntax.
# And(Condition1, Condition2) is also a meta-level construct.
